<paragraph id="8BF9368F292EFFB020FFE6BA95189609" blockId="5.[136,1452,1166,2021]" pageId="5" pageNumber="250">
Scrambler described as liana or climber to 
<specimenCount id="9D40FD06292EFFB0221CE6BA95FB95AC" box="[619,683,1166,1193]" pageId="5" pageNumber="250" type="generic">
<quantity id="4CBE9B6A292EFFB0221CE6BA95F795AC" box="[619,679,1166,1193]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="250" unit="m" value="10.0">10 m</quantity>
.
</specimenCount>
<emphasis id="B932EA9D292EFFB022C4E6BA946F95AD" box="[691,831,1166,1192]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="250">Indumentum</emphasis>
of hairs and scales: hairs 
<quantity id="4CBE9B6A292EFFB02415E6BA924495AC" box="[1122,1300,1166,1193]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.68" metricValueMax="11.2" metricValueMin="0.16" pageId="5" pageNumber="250" unit="mm" value="0.568" valueMax="1.12" valueMin="0.016">0.016–1.12 mm</quantity>
long, gingerbrown, giving a hirsute, hispid or pilose appearance throughout except the hypanthium; scaly on lamina surfaces, buds, inflorescences and fruits, scales peltate, up to 
<quantity id="4CBE9B6A292EFFB022E2E6E295AA95F4" box="[661,762,1238,1265]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="250" unit="mm" value="0.08">0.08 mm</quantity>
in diameter, creamy ginger, ± sessile, circular with irregular margins. 
<emphasis id="B932EA9D292EFFB02099E6CE96089411" box="[238,344,1274,1300]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="250">Branches</emphasis>
drying reddish brown with scattered indistinct lenticels, pilose, scaly to densely scaly on young parts. 
<emphasis id="B932EA9D292EFFB020FFE72B9786943D" box="[136,214,1311,1336]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="250">Leaves</emphasis>
: lamina ovate, 3.0– 
<quantity id="4CBE9B6A292EFFB021CCE72A9557943C" box="[443,519,1310,1337]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.5" pageId="5" pageNumber="250" unit="cm" value="8.5">8.5 cm</quantity>
long by 1.5–5.0 cm wide, sub-coriaceous, drying dark sage-green above, reddish brown below, adaxial surface sparsely pilose and scaly, densely so when young, abaxial surface pubescent with all hair 
<typeStatus id="54FD882D292EFFB020CDE75397A59484" box="[186,245,1383,1409]" pageId="5" pageNumber="250">types</typeStatus>
and scales; base cuneate; margins entire; apex acute or sometimes emarginate; midrib drying reddish brown, glabrous adaxially, sometimes sparsely hairy in young leaves, hairy to densely hairy abaxially with all hair 
<typeStatus id="54FD882D292EFFB02537E7BF922B94A0" box="[1344,1403,1419,1445]" pageId="5" pageNumber="250">types</typeStatus>
and scales; secondary veins 6–7 pairs, cladodromous–eucamptodromus, indumentum as lamina; petiole 
<quantity id="4CBE9B6A292EFFB0249AE79A923B94CC" box="[1261,1387,1454,1481]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" metricValueMax="11.0" metricValueMin="5.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="250" unit="cm" value="0.8" valueMax="1.1" valueMin="0.5">0.5–1.1 cm</quantity>
long, pubescent. 
<emphasis id="B932EA9D292EFFB02171E7E795F494E9" box="[262,676,1490,1517]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="250">Staminate inflorescences and flowers</emphasis>
not seen. 
<emphasis id="B932EA9D292EFFB02362E7E6937094E9" box="[789,1056,1490,1516]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="250">Pistillate inflorescences</emphasis>
lateral (axillary), racemes, solitary, sometimes with first order branching, 
<quantity id="4CBE9B6A292EFFB02241E7C295C79714" box="[566,663,1526,1553]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" metricValueMax="11.0" metricValueMin="7.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="250" unit="cm" value="9.0" valueMax="11.0" valueMin="7.0">7–11 cm</quantity>
long in fruit (not known at anthesis), axis hairy; pedicels 
<quantity id="4CBE9B6A292EFFB02553E7C292FC9714" box="[1316,1452,1526,1553]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.65" metricValueMax="1.8" metricValueMin="1.5" pageId="5" pageNumber="250" unit="mm" value="1.65" valueMax="1.8" valueMin="1.5">1.5–1.8 mm</quantity>
long, hispid and scaly; bracts triangular, 1.0– 
<quantity id="4CBE9B6A292EFFB022F2E42E95BA9730" box="[645,746,1562,1589]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.25" pageId="5" pageNumber="250" unit="mm" value="1.25">1.25 mm</quantity>
long, hispid, margins entire, apex acute; bracteoles ±opposite, inserted at the base of the hypanthium, shape as bracts, hispid abaxially, 
<quantity id="4CBE9B6A292EFFB023DCE40A9362975C" box="[939,1074,1598,1625]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6" metricValueMax="8.0" metricValueMin="4.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="250" unit="mm" value="0.6" valueMax="0.8" valueMin="0.4">0.4–0.8 mm</quantity>
long, 
<quantity id="4CBE9B6A292EFFB02401E40A93AD975C" box="[1142,1277,1598,1625]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="250" unit="mm" value="0.15" valueMax="0.2" valueMin="0.1">0.1–0.2 mm</quantity>
wide. 
<emphasis id="B932EA9D292EFFB02531E40A978A9779" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="250">Pistillate flowers</emphasis>
pentamerous; calyx lobes triangular, 0.6–0.9 long, 
<quantity id="4CBE9B6A292EFFB02358E45694979778" box="[815,967,1634,1661]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.25" metricValueMax="7.5" metricValueMin="5.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="250" unit="mm" value="0.625" valueMax="0.75" valueMin="0.5">0.5–0.75 mm</quantity>
wide, hispid and scaly abaxially, margins entire to ciliate, apex acute; corolla not seen; hypanthium 1.0– 
<quantity id="4CBE9B6A292EFFB0233AE4B294F497A4" box="[845,932,1670,1697]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" pageId="5" pageNumber="250" unit="mm" value="1.2">1.2 mm</quantity>
long, scaly to densely scaly; ovary 
<quantity id="4CBE9B6A292EFFB0254CE4B297E497C0" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.75" metricValueMax="4.5" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="250" unit="mm" value="0.375" valueMax="0.45" valueMin="0.3">0.30–0.45 mm</quantity>
long, 
<quantity id="4CBE9B6A292EFFB02176E49E96DC97C0" box="[257,396,1706,1733]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" metricValueMax="9.0" metricValueMin="7.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="250" unit="mm" value="0.8" valueMax="0.9" valueMin="0.7">0.7–0.9 mm</quantity>
diameter, style 
<quantity id="4CBE9B6A292EFFB0223FE49E958297C0" box="[584,722,1706,1733]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="250" unit="mm" value="0.25" valueMax="0.3" valueMin="0.2">0.2–0.3 mm</quantity>
long. 
<emphasis id="B932EA9D292EFFB02357E49F943497C1" box="[800,868,1707,1732]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="250">Fruits</emphasis>
globose, 
<quantity id="4CBE9B6A292EFFB023A0E49E933297C0" box="[983,1122,1706,1733]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" metricValueMax="3.5" metricValueMin="2.5" pageId="5" pageNumber="250" unit="mm" value="3.0" valueMax="3.5" valueMin="2.5">2.5–3.5 mm</quantity>
long, 3.0– 
<quantity id="4CBE9B6A292EFFB02496E49E926997C0" box="[1249,1337,1706,1733]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" pageId="5" pageNumber="250" unit="mm" value="3.5">3.5 mm</quantity>
diameter, sparsely scaly; pedicels in fruit 
<quantity id="4CBE9B6A292EFFB02187E4FA952897EC" box="[496,632,1742,1769]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.15" metricValueMax="2.8" metricValueMin="1.5" pageId="5" pageNumber="250" unit="mm" value="2.15" valueMax="2.8" valueMin="1.5">1.5–2.8 mm</quantity>
long; bracteoles remaining ±opposite each other at the base of the fruit; calyx lobes non-overlapping, persistent.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C35C6504292EFFB020CAE522938F9651" pageId="5" pageNumber="250" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BF9368F292EFFB020CAE522938F9651" blockId="5.[136,1452,1166,2021]" pageId="5" pageNumber="250">
<emphasis id="B932EA9D292EFFB020CAE52295409635" bold="true" box="[189,528,1814,1840]" pageId="5" pageNumber="250">Distribution and ecology:—</emphasis>
This species is currently known only from the 
<typeStatus id="54FD882D292EFFB0244DE523933A9634" box="[1082,1130,1815,1841]" pageId="5" pageNumber="250">type</typeStatus>
collection from 
<collectingRegion id="4982F86D292EFFB02547E52297BE9651" country="Papua New Guinea" name="Milne Bay" pageId="5" pageNumber="250">Milne Bay Province</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F351761F292EFFB0208DE50F96869651" box="[250,470,1850,1877]" name="Papua New Guinea" pageId="5" pageNumber="250">Papua New Guinea</collectingCountry>
. The plant was found in rainforest at c. 
<quantity id="4CBE9B6A292EFFB023E7E50E94879650" box="[912,983,1850,1877]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="250" unit="m" value="700.0">700 m</quantity>
(
<emphasis id="B932EA9D292EFFB02390E50E93419651" box="[999,1041,1850,1876]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="250">fide</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFD74B7E292EFFB0246FE50F93829651" author="Brass, L. J." box="[1048,1234,1850,1877]" pageId="5" pageNumber="250" pagination="77 - 152" refId="ref9586" refString="Brass, L. J. (1956) Results of the Arbold expeditions. No. 75. Summary of the fourth Archbold expedition to New Guinea. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History 111: 77 - 152. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 141745" type="journal article" year="1956">Brass 1956: 133</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C35C6504292EFFB220CAE56A95B592A8" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="252" pageId="5" pageNumber="250" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BF9368F292EFFB020CAE56A943596E1" blockId="5.[136,1452,1166,2021]" pageId="5" pageNumber="250">
<emphasis id="B932EA9D292EFFB020CAE56A9634967D" bold="true" box="[189,356,1886,1912]" pageId="5" pageNumber="250">Etymology:—</emphasis>
The epithet honours Leonard John Brass (1900–1971), an Australian-American botanist who collected the 
<typeStatus id="54FD882D292EFFB02154E5B796039698" box="[291,339,1923,1949]" pageId="5" pageNumber="250">type</typeStatus>
specimen of this new species. He participated in several important expeditions to New 
<collectingCountry id="F351761F292EFFB02524E5B692F79699" box="[1363,1447,1922,1948]" name="Guinea-Bissau" pageId="5" pageNumber="250">Guinea</collectingCountry>
, especially as the plant collector for the Archbold Expeditions, and collected many thousand specimens valuable for the study of New 
<collectingCountry id="F351761F292EFFB02151E5FE962796E1" box="[294,375,1994,2020]" name="Guinea-Bissau" pageId="5" pageNumber="250">Guinea</collectingCountry>
flora (c. 35,000 numbers – see 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD74B7E292EFFB022AEE5FF940896E1" author="Perry, L. M." box="[729,856,1994,2021]" pageId="5" pageNumber="250" pagination="695 - 698" refId="ref10891" refString="Perry, L. M. (1971) Leonard J. Brass (1900 - 1971), an appreciation. Journal of the Arnold Arboretum 52: 695 - 698." type="journal article" year="1971">Perry 1971</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption id="DF396607292DFFB320FFE578944E96CB" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5425473" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5425473" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5425473/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="251" startId="6.[136,229,1868,1890]" targetBox="[192,1379,213,1804]" targetPageId="6">
<paragraph id="8BF9368F292DFFB320FFE578944E96CB" blockId="6.[136,1452,1868,1998]" pageId="6" pageNumber="251">
<emphasis id="B932EA9D292DFFB320FFE57897AD9664" bold="true" box="[136,253,1868,1890]" pageId="6" pageNumber="251">FIGURE 3.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C464D0C292DFFB32174E579952F9664" authority="Sumanon &amp; Utteridge. A" authorityName="Sumanon &amp; Utteridge. A" authorityYear="2021" box="[259,639,1868,1890]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Primulaceae" genus="Maesa" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="6" pageNumber="251" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="brassii">
<emphasis id="B932EA9D292DFFB32174E57996D99664" box="[259,393,1868,1890]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="251">Maesa brassii</emphasis>
Sumanon &amp; Utteridge. 
<emphasis id="B932EA9D292DFFB32219E578952F9664" bold="true" box="[622,639,1868,1889]" pageId="6" pageNumber="251">A</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
habit of fruiting plant; 
<emphasis id="B932EA9D292DFFB32329E579943E9667" bold="true" box="[862,878,1869,1890]" pageId="6" pageNumber="251">B</emphasis>
node with petiole and inflorescence base; 
<emphasis id="B932EA9D292DFFB32573E57892459667" bold="true" box="[1284,1301,1868,1890]" pageId="6" pageNumber="251">C</emphasis>
abaxial surface of leaf; 
<emphasis id="B932EA9D292DFFB320A4E54597B49683" bold="true" box="[211,228,1905,1926]" pageId="6" pageNumber="251">D</emphasis>
part of infructescence; 
<emphasis id="B932EA9D292DFFB321BFE54596889683" bold="true" box="[456,472,1905,1926]" pageId="6" pageNumber="251">E</emphasis>
fruit apex; 
<emphasis id="B932EA9D292DFFB3223FE54595079683" bold="true" box="[584,599,1905,1926]" pageId="6" pageNumber="251">F</emphasis>
LS fruit (larger fruit than E, drawn at lower magnification); 
<emphasis id="B932EA9D292DFFB324D7E54493E39683" bold="true" box="[1184,1203,1904,1926]" pageId="6" pageNumber="251">G</emphasis>
scales on fruit surface; 
<emphasis id="B932EA9D292DFFB325EEE54592FC9683" bold="true" box="[1433,1452,1905,1926]" pageId="6" pageNumber="251">H</emphasis>
scales and hairs on pedicel. All from 
<emphasis id="B932EA9D292DFFB3219BE5A1953496AC" box="[492,612,1940,1962]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="251">Brass 23676</emphasis>
(K). Scale bars: single bar = 1 mm, graduated single bar = 2 mm and 5 mm, double bar = 1 cm, graduated double bar = 5 cm. Illustration by Andrew Brown.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="8BF9368F292CFFB220CAE2AA93D39095" blockId="7.[136,1452,158,941]" pageId="7" pageNumber="252">
<emphasis id="B932EA9D292CFFB220CAE2AA967691BD" bold="true" box="[189,294,158,184]" pageId="7" pageNumber="252">Notes:—</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C464D0C292CFFB22151E2AB969891BD" authorityName="Sumanon &amp; Utteridge. A" authorityYear="2021" box="[294,456,158,184]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Primulaceae" genus="Maesa" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="7" pageNumber="252" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="brassii">
<emphasis id="B932EA9D292CFFB22151E2AB969891BD" box="[294,456,158,184]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="252">Maesa brassii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinguished by its scrambling habit, being conspicuously hairy throughout with striking, ginger-brown hairs, entire leaf margins, and leaves drying dark sage-green adaxially and reddish brown abaxially. The indumentum of this species comprises both hairs of varying lengths and scales; the shortest hirsutellous hairs are found on the margins of the calyx lobes, while the longer hairs, giving a pilose appearance, cover almost all parts of the plant. The venation is quite distinct – the secondary veins branch quite early, usually just after halfway between the midrib and margin, and then diminish without clearly looping and joining and forming prominent marginal loops, somewhere between the cladodromus and eucamptodromus states of 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD74B7E292CFFB223AEE342932F9095" author="Hickey, L. J." box="[985,1151,374,400]" pageId="7" pageNumber="252" pagination="25 - 39" refId="ref10420" refString="Hickey, L. J. (1979) A revised classification of the architecture of dicotyledonous leaves. In: Metcalfe, C. R. &amp; Chalk, L. (Eds.) Anatomy of the dicotyledons. Clarendon Press, Oxford, pp. 25 - 39." type="book chapter" year="1979">Hickey (1979)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF9368F292CFFB220CAE3AF95B592A8" blockId="7.[136,1452,158,941]" pageId="7" pageNumber="252">
From the key to the species provided by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD74B7E292CFFB222D2E3AE940A90B1" author="Sleumer, H." box="[677,858,410,436]" pageId="7" pageNumber="252" pagination="39 - 65" refId="ref11112" refString="Sleumer, H. (1987) A revision of the genus Maesa Forsk. (Myrsinaceae) in New Guinea, the Moluccas, and the Solomon Islands. Blumea 32: 39 - 65." type="journal article" year="1987">Sleumer (1987)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C464D0C292CFFB2231DE3AF948F90B1" authorityName="Sumanon &amp; Utteridge. A" authorityYear="2021" box="[874,991,410,436]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Primulaceae" genus="Maesa" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="7" pageNumber="252" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="brassii">
<emphasis id="B932EA9D292CFFB2231DE3AF948F90B1" box="[874,991,410,436]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="252">M. brassii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
would key out to 
<taxonomicName id="4C464D0C292CFFB224C9E3AF923090B1" authorityName="Mez" authorityYear="1902" box="[1214,1376,410,436]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Primulaceae" genus="Maesa" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="7" pageNumber="252" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="rufovillosa">
<emphasis id="B932EA9D292CFFB224C9E3AF923090B1" box="[1214,1376,410,436]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="252">M. rufovillosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on the combination of pentamerous flowers, pubescent leaves and the racemose, many-flowered inflorescences and, indeed, this collection was included within cited specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="4C464D0C292CFFB2233CE3D794BA90F9" authorityName="Mez" authorityYear="1902" box="[843,1002,482,508]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Primulaceae" genus="Maesa" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="7" pageNumber="252" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="rufovillosa">
<emphasis id="B932EA9D292CFFB2233CE3D794BA90F9" box="[843,1002,482,508]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="252">M. rufovillosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in Sleumer’s revision. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD74B7E292CFFB22486E3D697EC9324" author="Utteridge, T. M. A." pageId="7" pageNumber="252" pagination="683 - 686" refId="ref11405" refString="Utteridge, T. M. A. (2013) A revised circumscription of Maesa ruficaulis S. Moore (Primulaceae-Maesoideae). Contributions to the Flora of Mt Jaya, XVIII. Kew Bulletin 68: 683 - 686. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 12225 - 013 - 9482 - 9" type="journal article" year="2013">Utteridge (2013: 684)</bibRefCitation>
discussed how Sleumer’s concept of 
<taxonomicName id="4C464D0C292CFFB2221BE033945C9325" authorityName="Mez" authorityYear="1902" box="[620,780,518,544]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Primulaceae" genus="Maesa" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="7" pageNumber="252" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="rufovillosa">
<emphasis id="B932EA9D292CFFB2221BE033945C9325" box="[620,780,518,544]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="252">M. rufovillosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was rather muddled and included a mixture of scrambling (‘climbing’) and shrubby/tree species, as well as species from primary or secondary habitats. With the description of 
<taxonomicName id="4C464D0C292CFFB220DFE07B964B936D" authorityName="Sumanon &amp; Utteridge. A" authorityYear="2021" box="[168,283,590,616]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Primulaceae" genus="Maesa" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="7" pageNumber="252" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="brassii">
<emphasis id="B932EA9D292CFFB220DFE07B964B936D" box="[168,283,590,616]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="252">M. brassii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
here, and the resurrection of 
<taxonomicName id="4C464D0C292CFFB22218E07B9451936D" authorityName="S. Moore" authorityYear="1916" box="[623,769,590,616]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Primulaceae" genus="Maesa" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="7" pageNumber="252" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ruficaulis">
<emphasis id="B932EA9D292CFFB22218E07B9451936D" box="[623,769,590,616]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="252">M. ruficaulis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<taxonomicName id="4C464D0C292CFFB2233EE07B94BA936D" authorityName="Mez" authorityYear="1902" box="[841,1002,590,616]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Primulaceae" genus="Maesa" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="7" pageNumber="252" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="rufovillosa">
<emphasis id="B932EA9D292CFFB2233EE07B94BA936D" box="[841,1002,590,616]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="252">M. rufovillosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD74B7E292CFFB22466E07A9381936D" author="Utteridge, T. M. A." box="[1041,1233,590,616]" pageId="7" pageNumber="252" pagination="683 - 686" refId="ref11405" refString="Utteridge, T. M. A. (2013) A revised circumscription of Maesa ruficaulis S. Moore (Primulaceae-Maesoideae). Contributions to the Flora of Mt Jaya, XVIII. Kew Bulletin 68: 683 - 686. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 12225 - 013 - 9482 - 9" type="journal article" year="2013">Utteridge (2013)</bibRefCitation>
, the limits of latter species are now more clearly defined: the sub-coriaceous leaves, drying dark sage-green adaxially and reddish brown abaxially, and the entire leaf margins make 
<taxonomicName id="4C464D0C292CFFB2221BE0A3958D93B5" authorityName="Sumanon &amp; Utteridge. A" authorityYear="2021" box="[620,733,662,688]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Primulaceae" genus="Maesa" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="7" pageNumber="252" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="brassii">
<emphasis id="B932EA9D292CFFB2221BE0A3958D93B5" box="[620,733,662,688]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="252">M. brassii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
very distinctive and easily separated from 
<taxonomicName id="4C464D0C292CFFB224CCE0A3920993B5" authorityName="Mez" authorityYear="1902" box="[1211,1369,662,688]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Primulaceae" genus="Maesa" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="7" pageNumber="252" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="rufovillosa">
<emphasis id="B932EA9D292CFFB224CCE0A3920993B5" box="[1211,1369,662,688]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="252">M. rufovillosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which has chartaceous leaves with serrate margins, usually drying dark brown above and pale sandy-brown below and hispid hairs. Both species are found in rainforest, but 
<taxonomicName id="4C464D0C292CFFB222FDE0EB947693FD" authorityName="Mez" authorityYear="1902" box="[650,806,734,760]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Primulaceae" genus="Maesa" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="7" pageNumber="252" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="rufovillosa">
<emphasis id="B932EA9D292CFFB222FDE0EB947693FD" box="[650,806,734,760]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="252">M. rufovillosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
seems to be scattered in lowland localities mostly near the coast. Unfortunately, there is currently only one collection of 
<taxonomicName id="4C464D0C292CFFB2235AE13794CD9219" authorityName="Sumanon &amp; Utteridge. A" authorityYear="2021" box="[813,925,770,796]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Primulaceae" genus="Maesa" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="7" pageNumber="252" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="brassii">
<emphasis id="B932EA9D292CFFB2235AE13794CD9219" box="[813,925,770,796]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="252">M. brassii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
making it difficult to determine the distribution and ecology of this species. Whilst there is no detailed label information, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD74B7E292CFFB223BBE11393C79245" author="Brass, L. J." box="[972,1175,806,833]" pageId="7" pageNumber="252" pagination="77 - 152" refId="ref9586" refString="Brass, L. J. (1956) Results of the Arbold expeditions. No. 75. Summary of the fourth Archbold expedition to New Guinea. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History 111: 77 - 152. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 141745" type="journal article" year="1956">Brass (1956: 133)</bibRefCitation>
states his collections on this date were made from a camp at 
<quantity id="4CBE9B6A292CFFB2225AE17E95269260" box="[557,630,842,869]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="252" unit="m" value="700.0">700 m</quantity>
in a mixture of primary and secondary habitats at the junction between lowland rain forest and oak montane forests. More collecting is needed in the Owen Stanley Range in 
<collectingCountry id="F351761F292CFFB2255EE15B978992A9" name="Papua New Guinea" pageId="7" pageNumber="252">Papua New Guinea</collectingCountry>
to better understand the ecology of 
<taxonomicName id="4C464D0C292CFFB2221BE1A7958E92A9" authorityName="Sumanon &amp; Utteridge. A" authorityYear="2021" box="[620,734,914,940]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Primulaceae" genus="Maesa" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="7" pageNumber="252" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="brassii">
<emphasis id="B932EA9D292CFFB2221BE1A7958E92A9" box="[620,734,914,940]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="252">M. brassii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
